description.value: Hollow terracotta figure of Isis-Thermuthis in a shrine, on a low plinth, with a snake body surmounted by her head. The back is largely plain, except for a curved groove interrupted by a break and a relief device which resembles the letter delta. Much of the upper part is missing, including a large piece of the head of Isis and any crown she may have worn. Two-piece mould. Micaceous red-brown Nile silt, with a brown surface and white inclusions. White dressing over the front (with runs behind). Pink paint on the flanking uprights of the shrine, along the top of the plinth and in the coils of the snake body; also on the lips of Isis and in bands indicating the ventral shields of the cobra. Black paint details Isis’s hair and eyes, and crosses the snake’s upper body.
